WEBVTT
Kind: captions
Language: en

00:00:01.640 --> 00:00:06.730
&gt;&gt;Female Presenter: And I'm really excited
to introduce our speaker for all you here

00:00:06.730 --> 00:00:12.560
today. His name is Bill Wallauer. And he's
from the Jane Goodall Institute. So, let me

00:00:12.560 --> 00:00:19.109
tell you a few fun facts about Bill. All right,
fact number one: For 15 years, Bill spent

00:00:19.109 --> 00:00:22.289
almost every day following chimpanzees in
Tanzania and Africa.

00:00:22.289 --> 00:00:28.720
And during that time, he spent more time with
chimpanzees than he did with humans. Fact

00:00:28.720 --> 00:00:32.590
number two: Bill has served as a cameraman
and scientific adviser for more than 30 shows

00:00:32.590 --> 00:00:36.600
on the BBC, Animal Planet, and The Discovery
Channel, including the very popular "Planet

00:00:36.600 --> 00:00:41.469
Earth" series. Fact number three: In the early
1990s, he successfully captured a video of

00:00:41.469 --> 00:00:52.670
wild chimpanzees giving birth on tape and
got asked by Jane Goodall to join the Jane

00:00:52.670 --> 00:00:54.070
Goodall Institute.

00:00:54.070 --> 00:01:01.070
&gt;&gt;Bill Wallauer: So, thanks so much for coming
out. My name is Bill Wallauer. And I think

00:01:01.070 --> 00:01:04.850
you can see from that video, I kinda like
my job. So maybe next to a Google employee,

00:01:04.850 --> 00:01:09.620
I'm probably the most happily employed employee
on the planet.

00:01:09.620 --> 00:01:10.620
[laughter]

00:01:10.620 --> 00:01:14.770
Yeah, I keep reading how this is the best
place in the world to work. And I keep thinking,

00:01:14.770 --> 00:01:17.960
"They've never been in my forest."

00:01:17.960 --> 00:01:19.640
[laughter]

00:01:19.640 --> 00:01:26.700
Anyway, this next slide. Have any of you ever
seen a Jane Goodall talk? A couple of you.

00:01:26.700 --> 00:01:32.170
And Jane, I got a message from Jane to send
a greeting. And we've already heard that greeting.

00:01:32.170 --> 00:01:37.880
But let's hear it again. This is Jane with
her classic chimp greeting to all of you.

00:01:37.880 --> 00:01:44.909
[Jane Goodall makes chimpanzee sounds]

00:01:44.909 --> 00:01:48.900
And that's that wonderful chimp call, which
we've been hearing in the forest now. Me,

00:01:48.900 --> 00:01:53.781
for 20 years. Jane, for about 60 years, as
we go through the forest. And that's just

00:01:53.781 --> 00:01:55.790
a chimp greeting to all of you from Jane.

00:01:55.790 --> 00:02:01.649
Thanks so much for coming out. So, a lot of
people ask me now how do they get involved

00:02:01.649 --> 00:02:06.079
in this work? And I have really three people
to credit, my mom on the left side. This is

00:02:06.079 --> 00:02:14.360
my mom as she was growing up. She was from
the East Coast, a traveler, English teacher,

00:02:14.360 --> 00:02:18.709
very cultured, from Charlottesville. My father
on the top right, he was a professional rodeo

00:02:18.709 --> 00:02:19.709
cowboy.

00:02:19.709 --> 00:02:24.400
Grew up in the mountains in California. And
so, I got this great mix of both worlds. So,

00:02:24.400 --> 00:02:29.000
we'd be at a Shakespearean festival in Ashland
one weekend and then Dad and I would go up

00:02:29.000 --> 00:02:34.710
to Northeastern Oregon and go fishing the
next weekend. And so, I'm from Oregon originally.

00:02:34.710 --> 00:02:38.830
And so, I owe--. Is somebody from Oregon here?
Yay.

00:02:38.830 --> 00:02:39.830
[laughter]

00:02:39.830 --> 00:02:46.110
A great state. And so, I owe them just so
much for giving me that sense of wonder about

00:02:46.110 --> 00:02:52.580
both human culture and also about wildlife.
And it's just been a wonderful ride. And then,

00:02:52.580 --> 00:02:55.740
of course, Jane Goodall, who always a hero.

00:02:55.740 --> 00:03:02.400
I met her as a Peace Corp volunteer in 1989,
and instantly fell in love with her and her

00:03:02.400 --> 00:03:06.879
mission. Yeah, to find out more about that
mission, I really encourage you to find out

00:03:06.879 --> 00:03:13.099
more about her. She is certainly a pioneer
in more than just chimp research in conservation,

00:03:13.099 --> 00:03:19.160
in the way she views the world. She is a true
living philosopher and visionary.

00:03:19.160 --> 00:03:26.350
So, from my background, climbing around these
hills and mountains in Oregon gave me a very,

00:03:26.350 --> 00:03:32.860
very good background to do the same kind of
work that Jane did in the early 1960s. And

00:03:32.860 --> 00:03:37.670
so, it's not such a different forest. Very
different climate, but not such a different

00:03:37.670 --> 00:03:43.260
forest. So I just, with my two years in the
forest as a Peace Corp volunteer and my knowledge

00:03:43.260 --> 00:03:46.319
of Swahili, I was the perfect fit for Jane.

00:03:46.319 --> 00:03:51.400
And this is what I looked like in, when I
first went out. I was in my mid-20s. This

00:03:51.400 --> 00:03:58.879
is about '92. And very, very green around,
green in the field; didn't know very much

00:03:58.879 --> 00:04:04.430
about chimps or very much about film-making.
And within a year of the Jane Goodall workout,

00:04:04.430 --> 00:04:06.220
I had totally gone bush.

00:04:06.220 --> 00:04:07.220
[laughter]

00:04:07.220 --> 00:04:11.910
You've all heard the Jane Fonda workout? Well,
that's got nothing on the Jane Goodall workout.

00:04:11.910 --> 00:04:12.910
[laughter]

00:04:12.910 --> 00:04:20.970
So, I totally got into it, went completely
bush. And just Jane, I filmed this birth that

00:04:20.970 --> 00:04:25.150
Winnie talked about. And Jane said, "Well,
why don't you just do this full-time? Let's

00:04:25.150 --> 00:04:32.420
get a research, visual imagery to go along
with the long-term data," which they had been

00:04:32.420 --> 00:04:34.660
collecting at that point for 30 years.

00:04:34.660 --> 00:04:40.370
So, now we have a thousand hours of research
footage of every aspect of chimp behavior.

00:04:40.370 --> 00:04:45.860
But then, film groups would come, film crews
would come and they would realize, "Well,

00:04:45.860 --> 00:04:50.550
wow. This is really steep and really thick
and our scientific adviser can actually get

00:04:50.550 --> 00:04:52.730
through this stuff just like a chimp can."

00:04:52.730 --> 00:04:57.380
And so, I would be keeping up with the chimps,
trying to radio them, "Catch up, catch up.

00:04:57.380 --> 00:05:02.130
All this stuff's going down." And they would
be a hundred yards behind me trying to keep

00:05:02.130 --> 00:05:04.990
up. And so, pretty soon they started giving
me the camera and teaching me how to shoot

00:05:04.990 --> 00:05:10.630
for film-making, which is a very different
art than doing chimp research home movies,

00:05:10.630 --> 00:05:12.660
which I was learning how to do.

00:05:12.660 --> 00:05:19.210
So, I got this great crash course in chimp
behavior from the chimps and in film-making

00:05:19.210 --> 00:05:24.820
from these visiting film crews. So, as Winnie
said, I worked on about 30, 35 films. And

00:05:24.820 --> 00:05:29.191
this pinnacle now is this; I think many of
you have heard about the "Chimpanzee" film

00:05:29.191 --> 00:05:35.130
by Disney Nature. I was one of the cinematographers
for that, which is, as a wildlife cameraman,

00:05:35.130 --> 00:05:37.570
just a dream job on so many levels.

00:05:37.570 --> 00:05:41.930
But particularly for me, because it gives
me a platform to actually come to people like

00:05:41.930 --> 00:05:48.210
you and talk about not only how amazing chimps
are, but the fact that within my lifetime,

00:05:48.210 --> 00:05:52.280
at the rate we're going right now with the
Equatorial forest, the African forests, they

00:05:52.280 --> 00:05:57.940
could be gone in my lifetime. So, that also
gives us a really amazing platform to talk

00:05:57.940 --> 00:05:59.290
about chimps and chimp conservation.

00:05:59.290 --> 00:06:06.350
So, Gaia still very much has my heart. And
it was absolutely amazing when on my visits,

00:06:06.350 --> 00:06:11.300
I would be there for ten, eleven months out
of the year, and you could imagine, like during

00:06:11.300 --> 00:06:16.390
the 90s, there was a lot going on technologically.
You might be aware of that. I missed all that.

00:06:16.390 --> 00:06:17.390
[laughter]

00:06:17.390 --> 00:06:21.690
And I just heard rumors about this Google
thing. I'm a real map person. I love my maps.

00:06:21.690 --> 00:06:28.750
I love being able to see where I'm going and
see where I've been. And you could imagine

00:06:28.750 --> 00:06:37.390
my delight when I could get on Google Maps
and mark the tree that Gaia was born in. I

00:06:37.390 --> 00:06:39.030
mean, is that cool or what?

00:06:39.030 --> 00:06:40.030
[laughter]

00:06:40.030 --> 00:06:43.970
So, you could go on Google Earth and check
out the tree that Gaia was born in. That is

00:06:43.970 --> 00:06:49.180
absolutely intriguing. You hear about Jane's
Peak. It was just off Jane's Peak in the tree

00:06:49.180 --> 00:06:52.130
that Gaia was born. But it's this tree.

00:06:52.130 --> 00:06:53.660
[laughter]

00:06:53.660 --> 00:06:57.810
For those of you who are scientist-minded,
this is Parinari curatellifolia was the species

00:06:57.810 --> 00:07:01.370
of the tree that she gave birth in.

00:07:01.370 --> 00:07:02.370
[laughter]

00:07:02.370 --> 00:07:09.160
And this is Gaia now. This is now 19 years
later. She has a baby of her own. And guess

00:07:09.160 --> 00:07:13.850
what we called the baby? We called it--. We
have G-family, so Gremlin had Galahad and

00:07:13.850 --> 00:07:16.110
Gaia, and Goldy and Glitter.

00:07:16.110 --> 00:07:22.110
Do you see the pattern there? Fifi has Freud,
Ferdinand, and Faustino. So, we named them

00:07:22.110 --> 00:07:27.680
through the female line by their--. And so
we thought, "Well, what would be an obvious

00:07:27.680 --> 00:07:33.620
name to name another G-baby?" So, there we
go.

00:07:33.620 --> 00:07:35.710
[laughter]

00:07:35.710 --> 00:07:37.800
[clapping]

00:07:37.800 --> 00:07:48.620
Born about June 4th, within a day or two of
June 4th, 2009. So, Google, meet Google.

00:07:48.620 --> 00:07:49.660
[laughter]

00:07:49.660 --> 00:07:53.780
And like the chimps, the chimps are obviously
aware that I am there, but don't think about

00:07:53.780 --> 00:07:59.100
me at all. But hopefully, you'll be involved
and follow Google's life. And she will never

00:07:59.100 --> 00:08:03.940
be aware of you. So, it's a very one-sided
relationship. But that's the way it has to

00:08:03.940 --> 00:08:08.630
be because that's one thing this movie has
been able, something it's been able to do

00:08:08.630 --> 00:08:12.610
for me is like, be a voice for chimps.

00:08:12.610 --> 00:08:16.490
And so--. We talked a little bit about my
background. Did you see the "Planet Earth"

00:08:16.490 --> 00:08:21.470
series? I mean, I haven't seen most of these
series 'cause I spend all of my time in East

00:08:21.470 --> 00:08:26.830
Africa filming, but "Planet Earth" was one
that I filmed, "Life of Mammals," both of

00:08:26.830 --> 00:08:32.150
which were produced and directed by Alastair
Fothergill, who came to me with this Disney

00:08:32.150 --> 00:08:33.150
idea.

00:08:33.150 --> 00:08:38.520
And that was one of the shortest decisions
of my life, next to saying "yes" to Jane,

00:08:38.520 --> 00:08:47.550
"Will I come to Gombe?" From 2008 to last
summer, I got to spend on and off three years

00:08:47.550 --> 00:08:53.820
filming for this Chimpanzee project for Disney
Nature, which was just wonderful. But what

00:08:53.820 --> 00:08:56.550
does it take to make it happen? They didn't
tell me about this part.

00:08:56.550 --> 00:08:57.550
[laughter]

00:08:57.550 --> 00:09:02.080
I kind of pictured, 'cause often I'd get a
shot list, which is the list of shots that

00:09:02.080 --> 00:09:06.562
a film crew wants. They don't even send a
producer. They'll just send a camera and a

00:09:06.562 --> 00:09:13.460
shot list and a tripod and I'll start my work.
We did that for "Planet Earth" and for "Mammals."

00:09:13.460 --> 00:09:19.020
And I did a couple BBC series. But in this
case, I stopped by Bristol, England to pick

00:09:19.020 --> 00:09:22.640
up equipment and I thought it was gonna be
a few boxes and bags.

00:09:22.640 --> 00:09:28.550
We had 22 hard cases plus our luggage plus
all our carry-ons. We were, my wife and I,

00:09:28.550 --> 00:09:33.400
my wife has done this with me for about ten
years now. She did the sound. So, when you

00:09:33.400 --> 00:09:37.560
go see the film, she did--. Just close your
eyes once in a while and just listen to the

00:09:37.560 --> 00:09:41.470
wonderful sounds of the forest. That's all
Kristin's sound.

00:09:41.470 --> 00:09:47.660
And she did the production stills as well
for this film. But yeah, the initial shock

00:09:47.660 --> 00:09:53.250
at having to carry and be responsible for
about 500,000 dollars' worth of boxes and

00:09:53.250 --> 00:09:59.380
bags and camera equipment was extraordinary.
And then the other thing, we get to our field

00:09:59.380 --> 00:10:05.280
site and then we have to buy two months' worth
of food to add another ten, twelve boxes to

00:10:05.280 --> 00:10:06.990
our boxes.

00:10:06.990 --> 00:10:12.090
And then, we'd also go to these wonderful
open food markets where--. I mean, I just

00:10:12.090 --> 00:10:15.960
experienced your open food market, which was
quite nice I'll have to say.

00:10:15.960 --> 00:10:16.960
[laughter]

00:10:16.960 --> 00:10:21.870
But there's nothing like an African open market
with all the tropical fruit: the mangoes,

00:10:21.870 --> 00:10:30.170
the pineapples and just all the food that
we can get. And we loaded up and happiness

00:10:30.170 --> 00:10:32.850
is seeing this city in my rear view mirror.

00:10:32.850 --> 00:10:40.590
You can imagine. Hit the open road and it's
just extraordinary. That shot on the left,

00:10:40.590 --> 00:10:47.740
a beautiful lake in the middle of Africa,
but not every scene we see is amazing. I mean,

00:10:47.740 --> 00:10:53.240
this is chimp's habitat and the distance in
this upper right shot, but that's a tea plantation

00:10:53.240 --> 00:10:58.000
surrounding it. You get the same in all over
West Africa: coffee, chocolate.

00:10:58.000 --> 00:11:04.010
There's a lot of unsustainable removal of
these forests for the things that we in the

00:11:04.010 --> 00:11:09.880
West and East have a hugely high demand for.
So, part of our messaging is as far as a conservation

00:11:09.880 --> 00:11:13.930
organization is make sure you know where you're
buying and eating that stuff. Make sure you

00:11:13.930 --> 00:11:18.690
know where it comes from because if we don't,
the result of that, like the African hardwood

00:11:18.690 --> 00:11:25.571
demand, which is pretty much developed country-wide,
you can buy all kinds of African hardwood

00:11:25.571 --> 00:11:26.571
in this country.

00:11:26.571 --> 00:11:31.220
Just be sure you know where your wood's coming
from when you need to build something. Obviously,

00:11:31.220 --> 00:11:35.130
we need to keep utilizing. We need to keep
building. It's just a matter of sustainability.

00:11:35.130 --> 00:11:40.460
I have a feeling I'm preaching to the choir
here, but it's still worth saying. And so,

00:11:40.460 --> 00:11:46.470
this is, as soon as we turn off the main road,
this is what the road looks like. It is extraordinary

00:11:46.470 --> 00:11:50.040
getting to the field site, about a nine and
a half hour drive.

00:11:50.040 --> 00:11:54.870
And then, we enter this forest, this magical
kingdom of the chimps, which you'll see in

00:11:54.870 --> 00:12:01.730
the film. I hope you all plan on going. It's
just an amazing, amazing place, this magical,

00:12:01.730 --> 00:12:11.350
150-, 200-foot canopy. Layers of canopy unlike
anything we see here anymore. It's still untouched,

00:12:11.350 --> 00:12:17.550
phenomenally beautiful and absolutely worth
saving.

00:12:17.550 --> 00:12:23.340
And this is home sweet home. We lived in this
tent, on and off. We have a little hut in

00:12:23.340 --> 00:12:29.270
Gombe National Park, where Kristin and I have
lived for 12 years together. But in this field

00:12:29.270 --> 00:12:35.490
site, we just lived in this tent. And on the
right is our technology base tent. So, I would

00:12:35.490 --> 00:12:40.850
have my computer, hard drive, HD screen.

00:12:40.850 --> 00:12:45.130
Kristin would have her stack of hard drives
for all her sound and stills. We ran that

00:12:45.130 --> 00:12:50.170
off both solar and a little generator. And
so, we would come back from ten, eleven hours

00:12:50.170 --> 00:12:58.430
in the field and then have to download 50
Gigs of data from our computers. And we could

00:12:58.430 --> 00:13:03.220
not have done this without the amazing crew,
the field assistance there.

00:13:03.220 --> 00:13:08.410
So, I wanted to show you, this is our group,
but Kristin's not in it because she's always

00:13:08.410 --> 00:13:13.440
taking the pictures. So, I finally got her
in front of the camera for this one. This

00:13:13.440 --> 00:13:24.530
is just on a break during a shooting day in
the forest. And this is our commute to work.

00:13:24.530 --> 00:13:26.490
[laughter]

00:13:26.490 --> 00:13:30.990
There's no traffic except for the occasional--.
Occasionally, we would run into an elephant

00:13:30.990 --> 00:13:35.990
herd and that's like, serious traffic because
you are stopped in your tracks for a long

00:13:35.990 --> 00:13:42.200
time because they will spread out. And if
they run into you in this forest, it's like

00:13:42.200 --> 00:13:47.870
you can't see the traffic. It's stopping you
because if you run head to head in a mom who

00:13:47.870 --> 00:13:50.250
has a kid, it can be really, really dangerous.

00:13:50.250 --> 00:13:55.990
But you would know they were there. You could
hear them rumbling. They do this deep [elephant

00:13:55.990 --> 00:14:00.350
rumble noise]. You hear this sound in the
forest like, "Oh, shh."

00:14:00.350 --> 00:14:01.350
[laughter]

00:14:01.350 --> 00:14:08.270
"What's gonna happen?" And so, you back off
and look where you need to go and try to get

00:14:08.270 --> 00:14:14.200
around them. But I just thought this shot
was fun. Can we get those lights? I didn't

00:14:14.200 --> 00:14:17.060
know those were so bright. Can we kill those?

00:14:17.060 --> 00:14:18.589
&gt;&gt;Male #1: Then we can't see you.

00:14:18.589 --> 00:14:23.510
&gt;&gt;Bill Wallauer: That's OK. Oh, it's not OK
for you as a videographer. I have no sympathy

00:14:23.510 --> 00:14:26.740
for you. I was filming in a black forest.

00:14:26.740 --> 00:14:27.810
[laughter]

00:14:27.810 --> 00:14:32.500
Dark chimps in a black forest. Come on. Man
up here.

00:14:32.500 --> 00:14:34.490
[laughter]

00:14:34.490 --> 00:14:39.670
Anyway, if there wasn't this light on me,
you could see the--. Well, you can see on

00:14:39.670 --> 00:14:45.960
the left side. This is an elephant footprint.
[tearing sound] All the way around here. I

00:14:45.960 --> 00:14:48.180
just love this because there's a chimp footprint
in it.

00:14:48.180 --> 00:14:55.030
There's a baboon. Bush pig. And up at the
top, just out of the frame, is a buffalo print.

00:14:55.030 --> 00:15:01.561
They also clog the road a little bit if there's
a herd of buffalo. You stop and reroute. Your

00:15:01.561 --> 00:15:02.960
GPS says, "Rerouting."

00:15:02.960 --> 00:15:03.960
[laughter]

00:15:03.960 --> 00:15:10.640
"There's a baboon trail a hundred yards behind
you and take a left." And we're also an all-weather

00:15:10.640 --> 00:15:17.890
crew. A lot of our work, it's not rain-dependent.
And so, and you'll see in the sequence, actually

00:15:17.890 --> 00:15:23.790
we got some really, really amazing rain dances
and rain displays as they were, as one community

00:15:23.790 --> 00:15:25.680
was being aggressive towards another.

00:15:25.680 --> 00:15:30.700
And so, it actually turned out to be really,
really important stuff to be able to shoot

00:15:30.700 --> 00:15:36.060
in this kind of rain. And also, watch where
you step. If you can't--. There are days that

00:15:36.060 --> 00:15:41.620
you can't find chimps. And you just walk and
walk and search and search, but those days

00:15:41.620 --> 00:15:44.470
aren't boring 'cause you've run into people
like this.

00:15:44.470 --> 00:15:51.310
This was about a seven-inch tall praying mantis
and rather than scurrying away scared this

00:15:51.310 --> 00:15:55.540
thing--. I jumped out of my skin, I tell you,
because I'm always aware of snakes, whatever

00:15:55.540 --> 00:15:58.490
might be on the ground. And this thing jumped
up like this--

00:15:58.490 --> 00:15:59.490
[laughter]

00:15:59.490 --> 00:16:04.300
and I jumped over there. Then, I walked towards
it to take a picture and the thing came towards

00:16:04.300 --> 00:16:05.840
me like this.

00:16:05.840 --> 00:16:06.840
[laughter]

00:16:06.840 --> 00:16:13.420
It's like, "No way." So, I don't know. It's
like everything in that forest is fascinating.

00:16:13.420 --> 00:16:14.880
[laughter]

00:16:14.880 --> 00:16:20.089
Even the snakes are fascinating. This is a
rhinoceros viper. You can see the little,

00:16:20.089 --> 00:16:26.540
I think those must be like nose smell sensors
that it's got. So, it has incredibly good

00:16:26.540 --> 00:16:31.740
sense of smell and feel. And it was hiding
in the vegetation.

00:16:31.740 --> 00:16:35.810
And the chimps streamed right past it. You
think the chimps are gonna be tuned in to

00:16:35.810 --> 00:16:39.601
all the dangers around them. Well, there was
an estrous female there at the time. There's

00:16:39.601 --> 00:16:44.230
a very popular female. They didn't even see
the snake at all. And they walked right past

00:16:44.230 --> 00:16:47.630
it. I saw it kind of move, so I got a few
shots of it.

00:16:47.630 --> 00:16:52.339
And so, I told everybody there was a snake
right there. Be really careful of that spot.

00:16:52.339 --> 00:16:56.200
And you could hardly see it. And then, the
chimps started to compete over this female.

00:16:56.200 --> 00:16:59.510
And so what did I do? I pick up my camera
and run right over here and start filming.

00:16:59.510 --> 00:17:00.510
[laughter]

00:17:00.510 --> 00:17:05.260
And it's only after the thing calmed down,
all this aggression calmed down, that I realized

00:17:05.260 --> 00:17:11.290
I was standing right next to the snake, who
just took pity on my stupidity and allowed

00:17:11.290 --> 00:17:18.339
me to live another day. Now, this guy came
right into camp. I thought it was a lobster,

00:17:18.339 --> 00:17:19.480
but--.

00:17:19.480 --> 00:17:20.620
[laughter]

00:17:20.620 --> 00:17:27.410
It's a scorpion. Again, about six, seven inches
long, extraordinary and actually probably

00:17:27.410 --> 00:17:32.440
less poisonous than the little tiny ones that
crawl into your clothes. Kristin did get stung

00:17:32.440 --> 00:17:36.880
by one on the hand just going through paperwork.

00:17:36.880 --> 00:17:41.679
And it put her out for about three days. She
hardly moved. Just moving her arm was agony

00:17:41.679 --> 00:17:47.480
for three days. It was just awful. But not
everything in the forest is awful. I had to

00:17:47.480 --> 00:17:52.970
throw this in for the Disney talk just because
of the Bambi effect of this little guy. We

00:17:52.970 --> 00:17:59.290
were listening for chimps one day and this
little person came out of the forest and just

00:17:59.290 --> 00:18:03.410
looking around, looked a little bit lost,
couldn't find mom and it's just adorable.

00:18:03.410 --> 00:18:08.600
So, a lot of the wildlife, the birds and the
other wildlife, just fascinating as well.

00:18:08.600 --> 00:18:14.240
So, what do I carry on my commute? People
ask me this all the time. And so, I decided

00:18:14.240 --> 00:18:21.930
to just spread invisible Bill out on a table.
And so, I wear these big rubber boots to get

00:18:21.930 --> 00:18:24.950
through those swamps. Ankle braces on both
sides.

00:18:24.950 --> 00:18:29.080
Knee braces on both sides. I've been doing
this for 20 years. So, my joints are getting

00:18:29.080 --> 00:18:35.600
a little bit stiff. Usually wear shorts. And
I take a little hand-held radio, so I can

00:18:35.600 --> 00:18:45.110
talk in Swahili to the field assistance there.
Swiss Army knife, a pair of binoculars, GPS,

00:18:45.110 --> 00:18:50.550
compass. The GPS is amazing because I can
figure out fig trees that are fruiting.

00:18:50.550 --> 00:18:54.970
And then, if the chimps are hitting even remotely
there, then the next day I can swing and get

00:18:54.970 --> 00:18:59.321
around them, be at the fig tree before the
chimps get there, being able to predict their

00:18:59.321 --> 00:19:03.430
behavior. So, that's another way technology
really helps out. And I threw a slide in here

00:19:03.430 --> 00:19:05.970
about that later on and then, my camera.

00:19:05.970 --> 00:19:11.830
You can see the camera was about this big.
So, just to put that to scale. And there's

00:19:11.830 --> 00:19:19.570
a rain cape underneath all that. There's plastic
bags to keep everything dry, a headlamp because

00:19:19.570 --> 00:19:27.540
we leave at dark and often come back at dark,
extra batteries. A little bit of food. And

00:19:27.540 --> 00:19:31.600
just some basic medical stuff and lots of
blister stuff. Go ahead.

00:19:31.600 --> 00:19:35.960
&gt;&gt;Male #2: So, they just released a whole
