00:26:28.650 --> 00:26:31.290
&gt;&gt;Female #1: How do you keep track of who's
who?

00:26:31.290 --> 00:26:35.940
&gt;&gt;Bill Wallauer: The same way you all keep
track of who's who here. And it's really strange.

00:26:35.940 --> 00:26:41.480
The first time you get there, you think, "How
can anybody tell all these chimps apart?"

00:26:41.480 --> 00:26:44.930
And now, I can hear their call from a half
a mile away and I say, "That's Freud. That's

00:26:44.930 --> 00:26:50.340
Frodo. That's Apollo. That's Atlas." It's
just like we do in our own culture, but it's

00:26:50.340 --> 00:26:51.340
interesting.

00:26:51.340 --> 00:26:56.760
I grew up in really rural Oregon and so, I
hadn't had a lot of cultural diversity, not

00:26:56.760 --> 00:27:03.840
in the school that I went to. And so, when
I first went to Africa, there was, I didn't

00:27:03.840 --> 00:27:09.110
have with African American faces, I didn't
have, or African faces, I didn't have that

00:27:09.110 --> 00:27:14.480
ability to differentiate different traits.
And this is true right across the board that

00:27:14.480 --> 00:27:20.400
we get used, in our own culture, the differentiating
traits that are familiar to us.

00:27:20.400 --> 00:27:25.630
And I had to learn that about chimps as well,
that though they all look the same, I need

00:27:25.630 --> 00:27:34.730
to use different cues that I'm used to using
to recognize people. And you do see that Lofty

00:27:34.730 --> 00:27:40.400
has a dark beard there. But they both have
black faces. So, in poor light conditions,

00:27:40.400 --> 00:27:44.650
you might get these two mixed up. But he has
a little bit of a tattered ear.

00:27:44.650 --> 00:27:50.450
So, over time, you get more and more accustomed
to figuring out who they are. And then after,

00:27:50.450 --> 00:27:57.040
like with this community, after being in Gombe
for 15 years and then following these guys,

00:27:57.040 --> 00:28:04.540
I guess within 2½ weeks, I had 35 of the
chimps down, committed to memory. So, and

00:28:04.540 --> 00:28:06.430
I'm not really very good with faces, human
faces.

00:28:06.430 --> 00:28:07.430
[laughter]

00:28:07.430 --> 00:28:15.250
And I just threw this in just to shout out
for my wife. My job is hard as a cinematographer,

00:28:15.250 --> 00:28:20.929
but I can always dial in some game and the
chimps are moving. For her, to get chimps

00:28:20.929 --> 00:28:26.310
to stop at that slow shutter speed, if any
of you are photographers or technicians, every

00:28:26.310 --> 00:28:28.480
once in a while all the elements come together.

00:28:28.480 --> 00:28:34.110
This beam of light came down onto Burg here.
And she can get these wonderful shots of his

00:28:34.110 --> 00:28:40.510
beautiful amber eyes. But it's so hard. Her
job is much harder than mine even. And then,

00:28:40.510 --> 00:28:42.320
here's our ultimate villain.

00:28:42.320 --> 00:28:43.320
[laughter]

00:28:43.320 --> 00:28:50.140
And you'll meet Scar in the movie. And this
is Scar. He's a grumpy old man, who is the

00:28:50.140 --> 00:28:52.330
leader of the villains.

00:28:52.330 --> 00:28:53.549
[laughter]

00:28:53.549 --> 00:29:00.480
And so, my job, a big part of my job was to
record this territorial behavior. So, we have

00:29:00.480 --> 00:29:05.601
Oscar and his group in the film. And then,
we have Hair and the villains, who'd come

00:29:05.601 --> 00:29:14.390
in and that's very true about the nature of
chimp society. Each community has a home range,

00:29:14.390 --> 00:29:17.340
which overlaps with three or four other home
ranges.

00:29:17.340 --> 00:29:22.430
And they compete for no man's land, or no
chimp's land, the overlapping territory. And

00:29:22.430 --> 00:29:29.320
if a strong community can, they will completely
take over another community. So, in this case,

00:29:29.320 --> 00:29:36.600
these guys--. And they're no better conservationists
than we've exhibited in the last 15, 20 years.

00:29:36.600 --> 00:29:40.350
These guys wiped out all of the colobus monkeys
in the home range.

00:29:40.350 --> 00:29:45.549
They hunted them down and ate all of them.
And so, they started going farther and farther

00:29:45.549 --> 00:29:50.660
out to patrol and search for monkeys, which
means they move farther and farther into the

00:29:50.660 --> 00:29:57.280
neighboring communities' range but also after
fruit and nut trees as well. The biggest challenge

00:29:57.280 --> 00:29:59.150
for me, though, was to actually get around
them.

00:29:59.150 --> 00:30:04.541
So, they're moving in these beautiful long
patrol-like lines. They stop calling. They

00:30:04.541 --> 00:30:10.090
stop exhibiting other behavior. It's very
much like a military patrol. It's just extraordinary.

00:30:10.090 --> 00:30:13.650
And so, my job is to get them, and you'll
see in the film, these shots as they're coming

00:30:13.650 --> 00:30:14.650
towards you.

00:30:14.650 --> 00:30:20.970
But that means I have to be traveling in faster-than-chimp
speed, which at times seems like it's faster

00:30:20.970 --> 00:30:25.140
than light 'cause they move so quickly. But
I did manage to get enough for this film to

00:30:25.140 --> 00:30:29.620
make a really powerful story. And another
thing I--. Oh, go ahead. Do you have a question?

00:30:29.620 --> 00:30:36.720
&gt;&gt;Male #5: Would you say you had a story you
create in the movie?

00:30:36.720 --> 00:30:37.720
&gt;&gt;Bill Wallauer: Yeah.

00:30:37.720 --> 00:30:38.720
&gt;&gt;Male #5: Or is this what you actually experienced
out there? Would you say they end up playing

00:30:38.720 --> 00:30:39.720
each other's characters?

00:30:39.720 --> 00:30:40.720
&gt;&gt;Bill Wallauer: Yes.

00:30:40.720 --> 00:30:41.720
&gt;&gt;Male #5: Is not really there?

00:30:41.720 --> 00:30:42.720
&gt;&gt;Bill Wallauer: Yeah.

00:30:42.720 --> 00:30:46.190
&gt;&gt;Male #5: And a lot of times, Disney is criticized
for doing the good versus bad, herbivores

00:30:46.190 --> 00:30:47.190
versus carnivores.

00:30:47.190 --> 00:30:53.280
&gt;&gt;Bill Wallauer: Absolutely. And I had to,
as primarily a researcher and research videographer,

00:30:53.280 --> 00:31:00.169
I go to these conferences, the International
Primate Behavioral Conferences. And so, I

00:31:00.169 --> 00:31:04.830
have a status as a behaviorist as much as
I do as a filmmaker. And so, I have to make

00:31:04.830 --> 00:31:08.540
sure my films are true to science.

00:31:08.540 --> 00:31:13.340
And of course, when you're shooting a film,
it isn't chronological. It doesn't happen

00:31:13.340 --> 00:31:18.170
just in the way. There's always going to be
some license, but the line we can't cross

00:31:18.170 --> 00:31:22.440
is the line of changing chimp behavior. And
of course, producers, who don't understand

00:31:22.440 --> 00:31:27.300
chimp behavior, are constantly saying, "Can
we say this? Can we say that? Can we say it

00:31:27.300 --> 00:31:28.470
this way?"

00:31:28.470 --> 00:31:36.040
"No. No and no." So, I choose my battles.
And if it's one over maybe a subtle vocalization,

00:31:36.040 --> 00:31:41.740
I might not fight that one as hard as I would
as if they were like, completely changing

00:31:41.740 --> 00:31:46.050
chimp behavior. But when they built these
villains up as villains, of course, in their

00:31:46.050 --> 00:31:52.200
own community they're not villains. They're
the same guys that you'll see in Oscar's community,

00:31:52.200 --> 00:31:53.559
Freddie and the bunch.

00:31:53.559 --> 00:31:57.559
But to the neighboring community, they're
very much. And those will be the guys that

00:31:57.559 --> 00:32:02.780
you see. Those are the chimps who you are
going to be scared of as a neighboring community

00:32:02.780 --> 00:32:08.840
member. And so, it is telling that story of
the way these overlapping communities defend

00:32:08.840 --> 00:32:14.750
and protect their territory and actually extend
their own territory into another's.

00:32:14.750 --> 00:32:20.440
And as far as character base, we did take
a little bit of licenses as far as Pincer

00:32:20.440 --> 00:32:25.850
is not the toughest chimp in the world. But
does that matter as much as the demonstrating

00:32:25.850 --> 00:32:30.330
the behavior well? And that's more important
to me. But it's a really good question. It's

00:32:30.330 --> 00:32:34.320
one we should rethink over and over. And I
appreciate questions like that.

00:32:34.320 --> 00:32:39.200
So, how far should I push those bounds before
we can say, "That's something I'm not proud

00:32:39.200 --> 00:32:45.690
of anymore." And I've actually taken my name
