00:42:59.979 --> 00:43:04.670
&gt;&gt;Jane Goodall: About seven years ago, I--.

00:43:04.670 --> 00:43:07.759
&gt;&gt;Bill Wallauer: That's just outside of Gombe
National Park.

00:43:07.759 --> 00:43:13.180
&gt;&gt;Jane Goodall: And I was absolutely horrified
at what I saw. So quickly it seemed the environment

00:43:13.180 --> 00:43:18.999
outside the National Park had been utterly
destroyed. The trees had gone. When I came

00:43:18.999 --> 00:43:30.750
in 1960, you could go in a boat and go right
up to Bolivia.

00:43:30.750 --> 00:43:36.789
It was chimp habitat. You could climb up the
hills of [ ] and look eastward--chimp habitat

00:43:36.789 --> 00:43:38.160
as far as you could see. And that's gone.
It's only within the 30 square mile path that

00:43:38.160 --> 00:43:42.459
the original forest remains. The question
then was, when people are struggling to survive,

00:43:42.459 --> 00:43:46.959
how is it possible to protect the precious
oasis of the Gombe forest with its very famous

00:43:46.959 --> 00:43:47.959
chimpanzees?

00:43:47.959 --> 00:43:51.359
And that's how TACARE came into being--a program
to try and improve the lives of the local

00:43:51.359 --> 00:43:58.609
people and the villages surrounding the path
and up and down the lake shore.

00:43:58.609 --> 00:44:00.319
[end video]

00:44:00.319 --> 00:44:04.911
&gt;&gt;Bill Wallauer: And so, that's our great
work is when you're working with people who

00:44:04.911 --> 00:44:12.809
are absolutely destitute in a country that's
arguably nine thousand miles away from the

00:44:12.809 --> 00:44:16.299
wealthiest country in the world, that is a
real challenge.

00:44:16.299 --> 00:44:21.009
You're seeing the forest on the outside of
the park disappear. You saw some of those

00:44:21.009 --> 00:44:29.499
shots. That was chimp habitat when Jane arrived
in 1960. And so, our huge challenge now is

00:44:29.499 --> 00:44:36.170
to slow down that tide and actually turn it
at some point. And Jane's visionary work not

00:44:36.170 --> 00:44:42.240
only was research in 1960, but realizing that
absolutely you have to work with and have

00:44:42.240 --> 00:44:44.780
people benefit from conservation work.

00:44:44.780 --> 00:44:49.359
And that's her other great pioneering work.
And so, we're not just a chimp conservation

00:44:49.359 --> 00:44:58.529
organization. We're very, very much both humanitarian
and many, many, many programs that I very

00:44:58.529 --> 00:45:02.710
much encourage you to check our website out
and look at Jane's vision. Read some of her

00:45:02.710 --> 00:45:05.640
books. But what are the threats to chimps?

00:45:05.640 --> 00:45:12.880
Certainly the global demand for African hardwoods
and the lumber that comes out of these forests,

00:45:12.880 --> 00:45:20.609
unsustainable agriculture, slash and burn
agriculture. The bush meat trade is also very,

00:45:20.609 --> 00:45:26.599
very devastating, has a very devastating impact
on chimps. And the illegal animal trade as

00:45:26.599 --> 00:45:33.470
well has a huge impact on chimpanzee populations.

00:45:33.470 --> 00:45:39.359
And so, with this demand, these are local
people are just struggling to make a living

00:45:39.359 --> 00:45:45.740
cutting down more forest, creating--. This
is just outside of chimp habitat. Trying to

00:45:45.740 --> 00:45:52.599
farm in these areas. And then resulting in
the soil washing down from the slopes and

00:45:52.599 --> 00:45:57.299
that all goes away. So, they start the whole
process over again, time and time again.

00:45:57.299 --> 00:46:04.430
So, this TACARE program that we've started
around Gombe, we're trying to emulate in sites

00:46:04.430 --> 00:46:12.000
right across Africa now. So, in Tanzania,
we have Tanzanian nurses going out, do interfacing

00:46:12.000 --> 00:46:17.869
with local people. We'll go to a village and
find out "What are your biggest needs?" "Well,

00:46:17.869 --> 00:46:21.019
we don't have a dispensary here." And so,
we'll raise funds.

00:46:21.019 --> 00:46:27.109
We'll work with local people. We'll start
a dispensary. And we have staff who are absolute

00:46:27.109 --> 00:46:32.559
experts in the field. We have a wonderful
savings and credit scheme, so that we train

00:46:32.559 --> 00:46:36.621
women up who actually invest in their own
scheme. A group of women will come and invest

00:46:36.621 --> 00:46:39.890
in their own scheme. We have a matching fund
for that.

00:46:39.890 --> 00:46:47.369
And that very much empowers women to be gainfully
employed using their own resources and their

00:46:47.369 --> 00:46:53.979
own businesses. In this case, this woman,
fabulous woman, had started a grain grinding

00:46:53.979 --> 00:46:58.400
system in her own little village. And now,
people are bringing grain to her and she's

00:46:58.400 --> 00:47:02.749
exporting that and she's making a lot of money
where she wouldn't have had this opportunity

00:47:02.749 --> 00:47:04.059
before.

00:47:04.059 --> 00:47:10.300
Also, inexpensive ways to solve problems.
Our team developed the Vetiveria grass, which

00:47:10.300 --> 00:47:15.529
is a bunch grass, which creates, when planted
across these slopes like this, creates terrace

00:47:15.529 --> 00:47:21.080
agriculture, which, terrace agriculture, there's
a real science, very difficult to do. This

00:47:21.080 --> 00:47:28.859
system is incredibly cheap, incredibly effective,
and this field will now be used for decades

00:47:28.859 --> 00:47:31.700
rather than for two years.

00:47:31.700 --> 00:47:38.640
And also, once we start protecting the forests
and start doing forest management, cash crop

00:47:38.640 --> 00:47:43.670
such as honey come into play in the villages.
And so, we have this honey distribution system

00:47:43.670 --> 00:47:51.959
and honey bee program, which helps local villages
to actually make money by having forest maintained

00:47:51.959 --> 00:47:54.190
and healthy.

00:47:54.190 --> 00:47:57.699
And also, I don’t know if you've heard about
Jane's Roots and Shoots program, but this

00:47:57.699 --> 00:48:03.369
is an amazing program. It's now in 130 countries
around the world. I encourage you to definitely

00:48:03.369 --> 00:48:09.069
look more into this. It's all about empowering
kids to make the world a better place for

00:48:09.069 --> 00:48:10.440
people, animals, and the environment.

00:48:10.440 --> 00:48:16.989
And what better message in this day and age
can you give kids? And it's got this global

00:48:16.989 --> 00:48:21.369
feel about it as well. So, kids in Tanzania,
they could be chatting with kids in China.

00:48:21.369 --> 00:48:25.940
They can be chatting with kids in the US,
all working towards those three main goals,

00:48:25.940 --> 00:48:31.859
which is just fabulous. And this story has
a very local feel.

